cff-version: 1.2.0
message: "If you use this work, please cite it as below."
title: "A signed-direction invariant for triangle tilings, and the exclusion of primes congruent to 3 modulo 4"
authors:
  - family-names: Bonfioli
    given-names: Vico
    email: vicobonfioli@gmail.com
abstract: >-
  Within the 2pi/3 branch of Laczkovich's classification of triangle tilings, a translation-invariant
  signed-direction functional proves that no prime number of 2pi/3 tiles tiles an isosceles triangle
  (for every prime; previously only a finite lower bound was known). With a self-contained reduction of
  the scalene shapes and machine-checked replacements for four of the five 3-alpha-2-beta targets, this
  excludes primes N congruent to 3 modulo 4 as numbers of congruent triangles into which a triangle can
  be cut, with one explicit exception: the base-beta candidates N = 3f^2 - e^2 (gcd(e,f)=1), an infinite
  family (11, 23, 47, 59, 71, 83, 107, ...) all congruent to 3 modulo 4, for which the only published
  exclusion (Beeson's Theorem 14) rests on a divisibility shown here to be false. These candidates satisfy
  every sound necessary condition and are settled individually by exact search; those searched up to 110
  (11, 23, 47, 71, 107) are excluded, and 59, 83 remain under search. In particular no triangle can be cut
  into 19 congruent triangles (19 is not of the exceptional form). The admissible spectrum of each sporadic
  branch is determined, the contiguous initial segment of the spectrum is settled, and realizations are
  exhibited: a triangle can be cut into 28 and into 44 congruent triangles, each certified by a zero-axiom
  Lean kernel computation; the 44-tiling of the (16,16,22) isosceles triangle by the (2,3,4) tile is the
  smallest known tiling in an incommensurable branch. The equilateral criteria reduce to divisor conditions
  and membership in the tile-count set is decidable. The arithmetic and combinatorial layer is machine-checked
  in Lean 4 with Mathlib (axiom-clean, no sorry). Developed with AI assistance (Anthropic Claude); presented
  for peer review.
keywords:
  - triangle tiling
  - Erdős problem 634
  - congruent triangles
  - discrete geometry
  - combinatorics
  - tiling invariant
  - Lean
  - formal verification
license: CC-BY-4.0
year: 2026
